    "course_credit_type" : "CU",
    "course_description" : "Raymond Williams coined the term \"mobile privatization\" to refer to the social vector that informed television as a technology. It has been used by media scholars first as a way of understanding the ensemble of technologies that captured previously public practices: just as television brought theater and motion pictures from public spaces into the home, so the automobile brought the streetcar into the garage, the telephone brought the streetcorner into the hallway, and the refrigerator brought the market into the kitchen. More recently, media scholars have used it to discuss new mobile communication communication technologies, most notably the walkman and the mobile phone. The proposed seminar will situate this familiar scholarship within a longer history of mobile privatization in western capitalist modernity. It will include scholarship on the history of apparatuses of mobility like legal and financial regimes, record-keeping and surveillance practices, and print media. Topics will include paper money, postal systems, photography, passports, and newspapers and other ephemera. In the background of such treatments are two larger concerns that will be introduced early and inform class discussions. The first involves the relationships among privacy, the public, community, and democracy.The second involves the relationship between mobility-as-freedom and control, particularly in the form of surveillance.",
