    "course_description" : "This course examines federal media regulations designed to protect children from potentially harmful media content (such as sexual or violent images) and media-related behaviors (such as on-line predators or disclosure of private information). We cover the history and philosophies that drive media policy and protect media institutions; policymakers' use of research and polls in developing regulations; industry implementation of government mandates; and the impact of children's media policies on those meant to benefit (namely, children and families). The course will cover policy across a range of media, including television, music, videogames and the internet. The focus will be on U.S. policy, though international efforts to address child audiences will be used as critical points of comparison. The seminar will be writing intensive, with students required to produce a 25 page term paper focusing on the implications of one on-the-books or under-construction federal regulations.",
