    "course_description" : "How valuable are 18-24 year old women and why? Should advertisers and cable channels focus on Baby Boomers, and if so why and until when, and with what kinds of content? What makes the \"Hispanic family\" a good target for marketers? To what extent and how are rich people different from those with less income, and what does it mean for targeting them with ads and content Questions such as these sit at the core of decision making in media industries. The ways media firms choose and understand their audiences have major implications for the content they produce and the platforms (broadcast television, Hulu, YouTube, Myspace, Facebook) on which they choose to exhibit or promote the content. Using a constructivist perspective, this course will explore the ways content producers and distributors construct their audiences. The seminar readings and the students' research will explore important changes that are taking place in audience research and market research, which lie at the center of these activities. Students will also have an opportunity to explore the rhetorics within the media and advertising systems that cause certain segments (eg \"African Americans,\" \"Asian Americans,\" or \"Teens\") to be constructed- and on the implications those activities hold for the content the audiences recive.",
