    "course_description" : "This seminar studies the power of new media practices by focusing on their formal qualities and emotional underpinnings and effects. The central question is the relationship between form and effect. We examine media forms from bulletin boards systems to blogs and Twitter, as well as forms of expression, especially rhetoric, symbolism, and style. The purpose is to explore how these formal features generate and sustain affective atmospheres and emotional energy in the new media environment. Besides theoretical explorations, the seminar requires considerable work with primary materials, such as monitoring and analyzing trending topics on Twitter. We look at both routine online interaction and moments of radical and viral communication. Of special interest are cases of online mobilization and protest, viral videos, and crisis communication. Case studies are mainly taken from China and the United States to enable cross-cultural comparisons. The main theoretical resources are drawn from the works of Georg Simmel (on social forms), Raymond Williams (on cultural forms and feeing), Dick Hebdige (on style), Jullien (on propensity in classical Chinese war strategies, rhetoric, and ), F. R Ankersmit (on aesthetic politics), and Kenneth Burke (on rhetoric and symbolism). A term paper is required.",
